# 🔗 Scalable URL Shortener

A URL shortener built with Django, designed to handle high traffic with caching, rate limiting, and asynchronous processing.

---
## 📌 Features
- URL shortening with unique short codes
- Fast redirection using Redis caching
- IP-based rate limiting to prevent abuse
- Asynchronous click tracking using Celery

## 🚀 Live Demo
https://urlshortener-prjs.onrender.com

## Load Testing Results — K6

**Environment:** Render free tier (0.1 shared CPU, 512MB RAM)  
**Tool:** K6  
**Test:** 50 concurrent VUs, 2m30s duration  

### Final Results

| Metric | Redirect | Shorten |
|---|---|---|
| p95 latency | 252ms ✅ | 916ms |
| p90 latency | 231ms | 880ms |
| avg latency | 148ms | 847ms |
| min latency | 94ms | 330ms |
| failure rate | 0.10% | - |
| threshold | <300ms ✅ | <500ms |

> Redirect endpoint meets the <300ms p95 threshold.  
> Shorten endpoint latency attributed to B62 encoding,  
> DB write + sequence fetch, and cache population on creation.  
> On dedicated CPU instances, both endpoints are expected  
> to meet thresholds comfortably (confirmed in local benchmarks).

### Improvement Over Initial Baseline

| Metric | Before | After | Improvement |
|---|---|---|---|
| redirect p95 | 3.17s | 252ms | **12x faster** |
| shorten p95 | 3.35s | 916ms | **3.6x faster** |
| service stability | crashed | stable | ✅ |

### Optimisations That Drove Improvement

1. Separated Gunicorn, Celery worker, Celery beat into independent Render services(as of now running only gunicorn due to render's free tier limitation)
2. `conn_max_age=600` — persistent DB connections per worker
3. Neon PgBouncer pooled connection string
4. Async analytics via Celery — removed Redis incr from redirect hot path  
5. `--workers 2 --threads 4` — 8 concurrent request slots on free tier

